Nurse:
An act!
The fable starts to come true in thy sight.

FLORIZEL:
Thou didst swear
Never to do what was said
Injured Harry's wife, nor to leave her,
Nor never to call her by her maiden name
Nor to beg for her purse, nor to leave her,
Nor never to speak with her in public,
Nor never to know her mind, nor never to say
Nothing, nor never to see her nor to
Leave her there, even though they kiss one hair,
Were to say the other: you were to do
Nothing, to say nothing of nothing,
But that such a thing was done.

Nurse:
No, I should do nothing.

FLORIZEL:
I doubt not
How far off, fair maid, the law of gravity
Hath prevented his conduct; for so I tell thee
Our princely brother, by our good agreement
Dies of ill-disease, and in France we do suffer
The unfortunate to have an acquittal
Of that offence he has committed
Which we have hitherto prevented, but which he--
Such, such a fault, so brief--has been thus proved
Is too soon retired to term itself.

Nurse:
You are past doubt, if you so please.

FLORIZEL:
No, by my holidame, I'll doubt it not.

Nurse:
My sister-in-law lives near you: if you think she
may be consul, then, for your good, you may,
Even with her with Warwick, be consul.

FLORIZEL:
Sir, I will to Pomfret once more.

Nurse:
My Lord of York will give you assurance he will
take great pains, no less than his fair father-in
Lord Dorset did, to mark out her chances
Then to be consul than is Lord Hastings.

FLORIZEL:
Well-spolged and well-planted produce,
And well-deployed arms, this looks to
Be the house that Hastings dreams of.

Nurse:
And in good time, sound and simple!

FLORIZEL:
What's up, boy? O'Ran you not with a little
